default.description: Storage-class specifier that declares automatic variables. Rarely used explicitly because local variables are auto by default.
Immediately exits the innermost switch or loop construct, transferring control to the statement following that construct.
Labels a branch inside a switch statement; execution jumps here when the switch expression matches the constant value given.
Qualifier that promises the compiler the object will not be modified through that identifier; enables optimizations and catches bugs.
Skips the rest of the current loop iteration and immediately begins the next iteration (re-evaluates the loop condition).
Labels the fallback branch in a switch statement; executed when no case label matches the switch expression.
Introduces a do-while loop: the body is executed once, then the condition is tested; repeats while the condition is true.
Introduces the alternative branch of an if statement; executed when the if condition evaluates to false.
Defines an enumeration type: a set of named integer constants that improve code readability and maintainability.
Storage-class specifier that declares a variable or function defined in another translation unit or later in the same file.
Introduces a for loop: initialization, condition test, and iteration expression grouped in one concise statement.
Unconditionally transfers control to a labeled statement in the same function; generally discouraged in modern code.
Conditionally executes a statement or block when the controlling expression evaluates to non-zero (true).
Storage-class hint requesting the compiler place the variable in a CPU register for faster access; modern compilers largely ignore it.
Terminates the current function, optionally passing a value back to the caller.
Compile-time operator that yields the size in bytes of a type or object; essential for portable memory calculations.
Storage-class specifier giving internal linkage (file scope) or static duration (preserves value between function calls).
Introduces a structure type: a composite variable grouping data members of (possibly) different types under one name.
Multi-way branch statement that transfers control to the case label matching the value of the controlling expression.
Creates a new name (alias) for an existing type; improves readability and simplifies complex declarators.
Defines a union type: all members share the same memory location; size equals the largest member.
Qualifier telling the compiler the object may change in ways the compiler cannot see; disables certain optimizations.
Introduces a while loop: repeatedly executes the body as long as the controlling expression is true.
Macro constant that represents a null pointer.
Smallest addressable integer type, guaranteed to hold one character of the basic execution character set (usually 8 bits).
Structure returned by div(): contains two ints—quot and rem—holding the quotient and remainder of an integer division.
Floating-point type with at least the precision of float; typically 64-bit IEEE-754 on modern platforms.
Single-precision floating-point type; usually 32-bit IEEE-754 providing ~7 decimal digits of precision.
Basic signed integer type whose width is chosen by the compiler for efficiency (commonly 32-bit today).
Structure returned by ldiv(): contains two longs—quot and rem—holding the quotient and remainder of a long division.
Signed integer type at least as wide as int; typically 32-bit on 32-bit systems and 64-bit on 64-bit LP64 systems.
Signed integer type narrower than int, guaranteed to be at least 16 bits.
Explicitly requests a signed representation for the accompanying integer type; redundant but can document intent.
Unsigned type returned by sizeof; large enough to represent the size of any object in bytes.
Declares the accompanying integer type to use non-negative values only, doubling the positive range.
Incomplete type representing ‘no value’; used for functions returning nothing or generic pointers (void *).
Wide-character type able to represent every character in the supported locales; often 32-bit on Unix, 16-bit on Windows.
Raises SIGABRT and terminates the program immediately without running cleanup handlers or flushing streams.
Returns the absolute value of an int; undefined on INT_MIN.
Returns the arc-cosine of x in radians; x must be in [-1, 1].
Converts a broken-down time struct to a fixed-format string like ‘Sun Nov 26 18:03:15 2025\n’.
Returns the arc-sine of x in radians; x must be in [-1, 1].
If the expression is zero, prints a diagnostic message to stderr and calls abort(); disabled when NDEBUG is defined.
Returns the arc-tangent of x in radians; range is [-π/2, π/2].
Returns the arc-tangent of y/x in radians using the signs of both arguments to determine the correct quadrant.
Registers a function to be called (in reverse order of registration) when the program terminates normally via exit().
Parses the initial portion of a string and returns its double value; behavior is undefined on overflow.
Parses the initial portion of a string and returns its int value; 0 if no conversion possible.
Parses the initial portion of a string and returns its long value; 0L if no conversion possible.
Performs binary search on a sorted array; returns pointer to matching element or NULL if not found.
Allocates memory for an array of nmemb elements, each of size bytes, and sets all bits to zero.
Returns the smallest integral value not less than x.
Resets both the error and EOF indicators for a stream.
Returns the processor time consumed by the program in units of CLOCKS_PER_SEC; divide result to get seconds.
Returns the cosine of x (measured in radians).
Returns the hyperbolic cosine of x.
Converts a time_t value to a 26-character English string in the same format as asctime().
Returns the difference in seconds between two time_t values as a double.
Performs integral division of two ints, returning a div_t that holds both quotient and remainder.
Causes normal program termination: calls atexit-registered functions, flushes streams, closes files, then returns status to the host.
Returns the base-e exponential function of x.
Returns the absolute value of a double.
Flushes and closes the given FILE; returns 0 on success, EOF on error.
Returns non-zero if the EOF indicator is set for the stream.
Returns non-zero if the error indicator is set for the stream.
Writes any buffered output to the underlying file; passing NULL flushes all open output streams.
Reads the next unsigned char from a stream, returned as int, or EOF on end-of-file or error.
Reads at most one less than size characters into s, stopping at newline or EOF; appends NUL; returns s or NULL on EOF/error.
Returns the largest integral value not greater than x.
Opens a file and returns a pointer to its FILE stream; returns NULL on failure, setting errno.
Writes formatted text to the given stream according to the format string; returns number of characters printed.
Writes the character c (converted to unsigned char) to the stream; returns c or EOF on error.
Writes the string s to the stream, without the terminating NUL; returns non-negative or EOF on error.
Reads up to nmemb elements of size bytes each from the stream into ptr; returns number of items read.
Releases memory previously allocated by malloc/calloc/realloc; passing NULL is legal and does nothing.
Breaks x into a normalized fraction and an integral power of two; returns fraction and stores exponent in exp.
Reads formatted data from the stream, storing values through the provided pointers; returns number of items successfully assigned.
Sets the file position indicator for the stream; returns 0 on success, non-zero on error.
Returns the current value of the file position indicator for the stream, measured in bytes from the beginning.
Writes nmemb elements of size bytes each from ptr to the stream; returns number of items written.
Macro equivalent to fgetc(); may evaluate the stream argument more than once.
Reads the next unsigned char from stdin, returned as int, or EOF on end-of-file or error.
Reads characters from stdin into s until newline or EOF, discarding newline; does NOT check bounds—deprecated/removed in C11.
Returns the absolute value of a long; undefined on LONG_MIN.
Multiplies a floating-point number by an integral power of two; inverse of frexp().
Performs integral division of two longs, returning an ldiv_t that holds both quotient and remainder.
Converts a time_t to a broken-down local time structure (accounting for timezone and DST).
Returns the natural logarithm of x; x must be positive.
Returns the base-10 logarithm of x; x must be positive.
Allocates size bytes of uninitialized memory; returns pointer or NULL on failure; alignment suitable for any object.
Lexicographically compares two memory blocks; returns negative, zero, or positive as s1 is less than, equal to, or greater than s2.
Copies n bytes from src to dest; behavior undefined if regions overlap.
Copies n bytes from src to dest; correctly handles overlapping regions.
Sets the first n bytes of the block pointed to by s to the specified unsigned char value.
Converts a local broken-down time structure to calendar time (time_t), normalizing out-of-range fields.
Breaks x into fractional and integral parts, each with the same sign; returns fraction and stores integer via iptr.
Prints the user-supplied string followed by a colon and the current errno message to stderr.
Returns x raised to the power y; domain and range errors are reported via errno & floating-point exceptions.
Prints formatted text to the console according to the format string; returns number of characters printed.
Macro equivalent to fputc(); may evaluate the stream argument more than once.
Writes the character c (converted to unsigned char) to stdout; returns c or EOF on error.
Writes the string s to stdout followed by a newline; returns non-negative or EOF on error.
Sorts an array using the quick-sort algorithm; user supplies comparison function that returns negative/zero/positive.
Returns a pseudo-random integer in the range 0 to RAND_MAX (inclusive); must seed with srand() for different sequences.
Changes the size of the memory block pointed to by ptr; may move the block; returns new pointer or NULL on failure.
Deletes the named file; returns 0 on success, non-zero on failure.
Changes the name of a file from old to new; returns 0 on success, non-zero on failure.
Sets the file position indicator to the beginning of the stream and clears error and EOF flags.
Reads formatted data from stdin, storing values through the provided pointers; returns number of items successfully assigned.
Assigns user-supplied buffer buf to the stream; passing NULL disables buffering; must be called after opening and before any I/O.
Fine-grained control: choose _IOFBF (full), _IOLBF (line), or _IONBF (none) buffering with a user or system buffer.
Returns the sine of x (measured in radians).
Returns the hyperbolic sine of x.
Writes formatted text into the provided buffer; user must ensure the buffer is large enough; returns number of characters written.
Returns the non-negative square root of x; x must be non-negative.
Seeds the pseudo-random number generator used by rand(); use a varying seed (e.g., time(NULL)) for different sequences.
Reads formatted data from the string s, storing values through the provided pointers; returns number of items successfully assigned.
Appends the entire src string to dest; assumes dest has enough space; returns dest.
Returns pointer to first occurrence of c in s, or NULL if not found.
Lexicographically compares two NUL-terminated strings; returns negative, zero, or positive.
Copies the NUL-terminated src string to dest; user must ensure dest is large enough; returns dest.
Returns the length of the initial segment of s consisting entirely of characters not in reject.
Returns the number of characters in the NUL-terminated string s.
Appends at most n characters from src to dest and always NUL-terminates; returns dest.
Compares at most n characters of two strings; returns negative, zero, or positive.
Copies at most n characters; pads with NUL bytes if src is shorter; does not guarantee NUL-termination if src is longer.
Returns pointer to the first character in s that matches any character in accept, or NULL if none.
Returns pointer to last occurrence of c in s, or NULL if not found.
Returns the length of the initial segment of s consisting entirely of characters in accept.
Returns pointer to first occurrence of needle in haystack, or NULL if not found.
Parses the initial portion of a string as a double; stores pointer to remainder in endptr if not NULL.
Breaks string into tokens separated by any character in delim; maintains internal state between calls; not thread-safe.
Parses the initial portion of a string as a long in the specified base (0, 2–36); stores remainder pointer in endptr.
Like strtol() but for unsigned long; correctly handles leading minus sign by wrapping.
Passes the command string to the host environment’s command processor; returns implementation-defined value.
Returns the tangent of x (measured in radians).
Returns the hyperbolic tangent of x.
Returns the current calendar time (seconds since epoch) as time_t; if timer is non-NULL also stores it there.
Creates a binary file that is automatically deleted when closed or on program termination; returns FILE pointer.
Constructs a unique filename that does not already exist; up to TMP_MAX different names possible.
Converts an unsigned char to lower case if it is an upper-case letter in the current locale; returns input unchanged otherwise.
Converts an unsigned char to upper case if it is a lower-case letter in the current locale; returns input unchanged otherwise.
Pushes c (converted to unsigned char) back onto the stream; only one character of pushback is guaranteed.
Pushes the wide character c back onto the stream; only one guaranteed pushback; returns c or WEOF on failure.
Expands to the next unnamed argument of the specified type; must be called once per argument in the order they appear.
Cleans up the va_list object after all arguments have been read; must be paired with every va_start/va_copy.
Initializes ap to point to the first unnamed argument after the fixed parameter last; must be called before va_arg.
Writes formatted output to the given stream using a va_list; useful inside custom printf-style wrappers.
Wide-character version of vfprintf; writes formatted wide text to the stream using a va_list.
Equivalent to printf but retrieves arguments from a va_list instead of the call stack.
Writes formatted text into the supplied buffer using a va_list; caller must ensure buffer is large enough.
Wide-character version of vsprintf; writes formatted wide text into a wide buffer using a va_list.
Wide-character version of vprintf; outputs formatted wide text to stdout using a va_list.
Converts a wide character to its multibyte representation, storing it via s and updating the mbstate_t object.
Appends the wide string src to dest; assumes dest has enough space; returns dest.
Returns pointer to first occurrence of wc in ws, or NULL if not found.
Lexicographically compares two NUL-terminated wide strings; returns negative, zero, or positive.
Compares two wide strings according to the current LC_COLLATE locale; useful for alphabetical ordering.
Copies the NUL-terminated wide string src to dest; user must ensure dest is large enough; returns dest.
Returns the length of the initial segment of ws consisting entirely of wide characters not in reject.
Formats broken-down time into a wide string according to the supplied format and locale.
Returns the number of wide characters in the NUL-terminated wide string ws.
Appends at most n wide characters from src to dest and always NUL-terminates; returns dest.
Compares at most n wide characters of two strings; returns negative, zero, or positive.
Copies at most n wide characters; pads with NUL if src shorter; may omit final NUL if src longer.
Returns pointer to first wide character in ws that matches any in accept, or NULL if none.
Returns pointer to last occurrence of wc in ws, or NULL if not found.
Converts a wide string to multibyte, updating src pointer and mbstate_t; returns number of bytes stored.
Returns length of initial segment of ws consisting entirely of wide characters in accept.
Returns pointer to first occurrence of needle in haystack, or NULL if not found.
Parses initial portion of wide string as double; stores address of remainder in endptr if not NULL.
Breaks wide string into tokens separated by any wide character in delim; maintains internal state; not thread-safe.
Parses initial portion of wide string as long in specified base; stores remainder pointer in endptr.
Converts entire wide string to multibyte; returns number of bytes stored, or (size_t)-1 on error.
Like wcstol() but for unsigned long; correctly handles leading minus sign by wrapping.
Transforms wide string so that wcscmp on transformed strings yields same order as wcscoll on originals.
Converts a wide character to a single-byte character if possible; returns EOF if no valid conversion.
Converts wide character to multibyte sequence, storing it via s and updating mbstate_t; returns number of bytes.
Locates first occurrence of wc in the initial n wide characters of ws; returns pointer or NULL.
Lexicographically compares two blocks of n wide characters; returns negative, zero, or positive.
Copies n wide characters from src to dest; behavior undefined if regions overlap.
Copies n wide characters from src to dest; correctly handles overlapping regions.
Sets the first n wide characters of the block to wc; returns dest.
Prints formatted wide text to stdout according to the format string; returns number of wide characters printed.
Reads formatted wide text from stdin, storing values through provided pointers; returns number of items successfully assigned.

name: Language Support for C
description: Autocomplete for C: keywords, common types, and standard functions.
